Merge pull request #285 from timcurzon/fseventstovmrunner-filepath-fix Naive fix to pass custom host mount dir to fsevents_to_vm

Naive fix to pass custom host mount dir to fsevents_to_vm The Unfs class correctly observes the DINGHY_HOST_MOUNT_DIR (+ DINGHY_GUEST_MOUNT_DIR) environment variable, but FseventsToVmRunner does not, so by default only fsevents generated in the users home directory are relayed.

This commit addresses that and allows DINGHY_HOST_MOUNT_DIR to effect the expected behaviour.

Merge pull request #228 from uberjay/sudo-set-home don't load ~/.gemrc when installing fsevents_to_vm

don't load ~/.gemrc when installing fsevents_to_vm This fix avoid loading the current user's gemrc both when probing if
`fsevents_to_vm` installed, and when installing it. If the gem is installed
using `--env-shebang` an incorrect ruby may be located (by searching the user's
`PATH`) resulting in a failure to start the FsEvents daemon.

Related to issue #227. `~/.gemrc` contained:

```
install: --env-shebang
```

squash NFS permissions to the home dir user This is less compatible with running Docker directly on Linux, where no
squashing occurs on host-mounted volumes, but it's a lot more convenient for
users and the edge cases where it makes a difference appear to be quite rare.

Example of an edge case where this breaks:

    > mkdir pg1 && docker run -v `pwd`/pg1:/var/lib/postgresql/data postgres
    chown: changing ownership of `/var/lib/postgresql/data': Operation not permitted

This fails because postgres requires the data dir to be owned by the container's postgres user.

This doesn't work on boot2docker either, with virtualbox built-in file sharing,
but for a different reason -- on dinghy with NFS, it fails immediately because
the `chown` isn't allowed. On boot2docker with virtualbox sharing, the `chown`
is silently ignored, and then you get an error later because the directory isn't
owned by the container's "postgres" user.

virtualbox: turn off host resolver and dns proxy This isn't ideal, since it means the VM will likely need a restart when
the host machine moves and DNS changes. But we're running into too many
issues with the host resolver, issues that look similar to
https://www.virtualbox.org/ticket/11663

disable vagrant ssh key replacement Vagrant replaces the insecure default private key, but doesn't
understand that boot2docker uses tmpfs, so the private key reverts on
next reboot, and vagrant can no longer ssh in.

This isn't an ideal fix, I'd like to support a custom private key
eventually, but it's equivalent to vagrant 1.6 behavior.
